macro.dbt_postgres.postgres__get_relatio.name: postgres__get_relations
macro.dbt_postgres.postgres__get_relatio.macro_sql:
{% macro postgres__get_relations() -%}

  {#
      -- in pg_depend, objid is the dependent, refobjid is the referenced object
      --  > a pg_depend entry indicates that the referenced object cannot be
      --  > dropped without also dropping the dependent object.
  #}

  {%- call statement('relations', fetch_result=True) -%}
    with relation as (
        select
            pg_rewrite.ev_class as class,
            pg_rewrite.oid as id
        from pg_rewrite
    ),
    class as (
        select
            oid as id,
            relname as name,
            relnamespace as schema,
            relkind as kind
        from pg_class
    ),
    dependency as (
        select distinct
            pg_depend.objid as id,
            pg_depend.refobjid as ref
        from pg_depend
    ),
    schema as (
        select
            pg_namespace.oid as id,
            pg_namespace.nspname as name
        from pg_namespace
        where nspname != 'information_schema' and nspname not like 'pg\_%'
    ),
    referenced as (
        select
            relation.id AS id,
            referenced_class.name ,
            referenced_class.schema ,
            referenced_class.kind
        from relation
        join class as referenced_class on relation.class=referenced_class.id
        where referenced_class.kind in ('r', 'v', 'm')
    ),
    relationships as (
        select
            referenced.name as referenced_name,
            referenced.schema as referenced_schema_id,
            dependent_class.name as dependent_name,
            dependent_class.schema as dependent_schema_id,
            referenced.kind as kind
        from referenced
        join dependency on referenced.id=dependency.id
        join class as dependent_class on dependency.ref=dependent_class.id
        where
            (referenced.name != dependent_class.name or
             referenced.schema != dependent_class.schema)
    )

    select
        referenced_schema.name as referenced_schema,
        relationships.referenced_name as referenced_name,
        dependent_schema.name as dependent_schema,
        relationships.dependent_name as dependent_name
    from relationships
    join schema as dependent_schema on relationships.dependent_schema_id=dependent_schema.id
    join schema as referenced_schema on relationships.referenced_schema_id=referenced_schema.id
    group by referenced_schema, referenced_name, dependent_schema, dependent_name
    order by referenced_schema, referenced_name, dependent_schema, dependent_name;

  {%- endcall -%}

  {{ return(load_result('relations').table) }}
{% endmacro %}

macro.dbt_postgres.postgres__list_relati.macro_sql:
{% macro postgres__list_relations_without_caching(schema_relation) %}
  {% call statement('list_relations_without_caching', fetch_result=True) -%}
    select
      '{{ schema_relation.database }}' as database,
      tablename as name,
      schemaname as schema,
      'table' as type
    from pg_tables
    where schemaname ilike '{{ schema_relation.schema }}'
    union all
    select
      '{{ schema_relation.database }}' as database,
      viewname as name,
      schemaname as schema,
      'view' as type
    from pg_views
    where schemaname ilike '{{ schema_relation.schema }}'
    union all
    select
      '{{ schema_relation.database }}' as database,
      matviewname as name,
      schemaname as schema,
      'materialized_view' as type
    from pg_matviews
    where schemaname ilike '{{ schema_relation.schema }}'
  {% endcall %}
  {{ return(load_result('list_relations_without_caching').table) }}
{% endmacro %}

macro.dbt_postgres.postgres__get_show_in.name: postgres__get_show_indexes_sql
macro.dbt_postgres.postgres__get_show_in.macro_sql:
{% macro postgres__get_show_indexes_sql(relation) %}
    select
        i.relname                                   as name,
        m.amname                                    as method,
        ix.indisunique                              as "unique",
        array_to_string(array_agg(a.attname), ',')  as column_names
    from pg_index ix
    join pg_class i
        on i.oid = ix.indexrelid
    join pg_am m
        on m.oid=i.relam
    join pg_class t
        on t.oid = ix.indrelid
    join pg_namespace n
        on n.oid = t.relnamespace
    join pg_attribute a
        on a.attrelid = t.oid
        and a.attnum = ANY(ix.indkey)
    where t.relname = '{{ relation.identifier }}'
      and n.nspname = '{{ relation.schema }}'
      and t.relkind in ('r', 'm')
    group by 1, 2, 3
    order by 1, 2, 3
{% endmacro %}

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.one_ho.name: one_hot_encode
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.one_ho.description:
This macro returns one hot encoded fields from a categorical column.

NOTE: One hot encoded fields will have the naming convention `is_{column_name}_{value}`

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be one hot encoded

arguments.name: source_relation
arguments.description: (optional) A Relation (a ref or source) that contains the list of columns you wish to select from

arguments.name: source_condition
arguments.description: (optional) A where clause condition to filter the field to be one-hot encoded by

arguments.name: categories
arguments.description: (optional) An explicit list of categories to one-hot encode into

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__one_hot_encode

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.poly_t.name: poly_transform
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.poly_t.description: This macro returns the given column after applying a polynomial transformation to the numerical data

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be transformed

arguments.name: degree
arguments.description: The degree of the polynomial transformation. Default is 2

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__poly_transform

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.random.name: random_impute
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.random.description:
This macro returns randomly imputed data for a column in a model or source based on values that already exist within the column

NOTE: This method assumes that at least one value has been observed in the input column

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be imputed

arguments.name: source_relation
arguments.description: A Relation (a ref or source) that contains the list of columns you wish to select from

arguments.name: data_type
arguments.description: The data type of this column. Either numerical or categorical

arguments.name: consider_distribution
arguments.description: Whether or not the distribution of existing values should be taken into account. Macro will run faster when this is set to false. Default is false

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__random_impute

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.rare_c.name: rare_category_encode
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.rare_c.description: This macro encodes rarely occuring categorical values with 'Other', leaving the rest of the categorical column values as is

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be rare category encoded

arguments.name: cutoff
arguments.description: The percentage value (in decimal) that is to serve as the point where any values occuring with a lesser frequency are rare category encoded. Default is 0.05 (ie 5%)

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__rare_category_encode

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.max_ab.name: max_absolute_scale
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.max_ab.description: This macro transforms the given column by dividing each value by the maximum absolute value within the column. This transforms the range of values within the column to be [-1, 1]

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be transformed

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__max_absolute_scale

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.expone.name: exponentiate

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__exponentiate

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.intera.name: interact
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.intera.description: This macro creates an interaction term between two numerical columns

arguments.name: column_one
arguments.description: Name of the first field in the interaction term

arguments.name: column_two
arguments.description: Name of the second field in the interaction term

arguments.name: interaction
arguments.description: The interaction to apply. Options are "multaplicative", "additive", "exponential". Default is "multiplicative"

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__interact

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.robust.name: robust_scale
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.robust.description: This macro transforms the given column into IQR scaled values to more effectively deal with concerning outlier datapoints

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be transformed

arguments.name: iqr
arguments.description: The interquantile range to consider and scale by. Expects a number between 0 and 1 excluse. Default is 0.5, leading to a interquantile range stretching from the 25th percentile to the 75th percentile

arguments.name: source_relation
arguments.description: (required for some databases) A Relation (a ref or source) that contains the list of columns you wish to select from

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__robust_scale

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.snowfl.name: snowflake__robust_scale

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.label_.description: This macro returns a the labels encoded with individual integers from 0 to n-1. Note that this has the side effect of re-ordering the dataset.

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be encoded

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__label_encode

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.k_bins.name: k_bins_discretize
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.k_bins.description: This macro returns the given column after discretizing it into a specified number of bins

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be k bins discretized

arguments.name: k
arguments.description: The number of bins to discretize into

arguments.name: strategy
arguments.description: The method by which to discretize the column into bins. Supported options are "quantile" to discretize into equal sized bins and "uniform" to bin into equal width bins. Default is "quantile"

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__k_bins_discretize

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.standa.name: standardize

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__standardize

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.numeri.name: numerical_binarize
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.numeri.description: This macro transforms the given numerical column into binary value based on either a specified cutoff value or percentile

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be transformed

arguments.name: cutoff
arguments.description: The value that serves as the boundary point for the binary variable. This should be a value between 0 and 1 for percentile cutoff's. Default is 0.5

arguments.name: strategy
arguments.description: The method with which to set the boundary point for the binary variable, options are "percentile" and "value". Default is 'percentile'

arguments.name: direction
arguments.description: The direction that the 1 value should signify for the binary variable. Options are ">", ">=", "<", and "<=". Default is ">="

arguments.name: source_relation
arguments.description: (required for some databases) A Relation (a ref or source) that contains the list of columns you wish to select from

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__numerical_binarize

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.snowfl.name: snowflake__numerical_binarize

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.catego.name: categorical_impute
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.catego.description: This macro returns impute categorical data for a column in a model, source, or CTE

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be imputed

arguments.name: measure
arguments.description: The columns containing the data you want to transform

arguments.name: source_relation
arguments.description: (required for some databases) A Relation (a ref or source) that contains the list of columns you wish to select from

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__categorical_impute

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.postgr.name: postgres__categorical_impute

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.log_tr.name: log_transform
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.log_tr.description: This macro returns the given column after applying a log transformation to the numerical data

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be log transformed

arguments.name: base
arguments.description: The base of the log function that is transforming the column. Default is 10

arguments.name: offset
arguments.description: Value to be added to all values in the column before log transforming. Common use case is when zero values are included in the column. Default is 0

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__log_transform

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.min_ma.name: min_max_scale
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.min_ma.description: This macro transforms the given column to have a specified minimum and specified maximum, and scaling all values to fit that range. This transforms the range of values within the column to be [new minimum, new maximum]

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be transformed

arguments.name: new_min
arguments.description: The new minimum value to scale towards

arguments.name: new_max
arguments.description: The new maximum value to scale towards

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__min_max_scale

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.numeri.name: numerical_impute
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.numeri.description: This macro returns imputed numerical data for a column in a model, source, or CTE

arguments.name: column
arguments.description: Name of the field that is to be imputed

arguments.name: measure
arguments.description: The measure by which to impute the data. It is set to use the 'mean' by default, but also support 'median' and 'percentile'

arguments.name: percentile
arguments.description: If percentile is selected for the measure, this indicates the percentile value to impute into null values

arguments.name: source_relation
arguments.description: (required for some databases) A Relation (a ref or source) that contains the list of columns you wish to select from

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__numerical_impute

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.snowfl.name: snowflake__numerical_impute

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.bool_t.name: bool_to_one_hot
macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.bool_t.description: This macro converts boolean columns to one-hot encoded format (0 or 1). It can handle multiple columns at once and provides options for handling null values.

arguments.name: columns
arguments.description: List of boolean column names to convert to one-hot format

arguments.name: null_as_one
arguments.description: Whether to treat null values as 1 (true) or 0 (false). Default is false

arguments.name: prefix
arguments.description: Prefix to use for the output column names. Default is 'is_'

macro.dbt_ml_inline_preprocessing.defaul.name: default__bool_to_one_hot

doc.dbt.__overview__.name: __overview__
doc.dbt.__overview__.block_contents:
### Welcome!

Welcome to the auto-generated documentation for your dbt project!

### Navigation

You can use the `Project` and `Database` navigation tabs on the left side of the window to explore the models
in your project.

#### Project Tab
The `Project` tab mirrors the directory structure of your dbt project. In this tab, you can see all of the
models defined in your dbt project, as well as models imported from dbt packages.

#### Database Tab
The `Database` tab also exposes your models, but in a format that looks more like a database explorer. This view
shows relations (tables and views) grouped into database schemas. Note that ephemeral models are _not_ shown
in this interface, as they do not exist in the database.

### Graph Exploration
You can click the blue icon on the bottom-right corner of the page to view the lineage graph of your models.

On model pages, you'll see the immediate parents and children of the model you're exploring. By clicking the `Expand`
button at the top-right of this lineage pane, you'll be able to see all of the models that are used to build,
or are built from, the model you're exploring.

Once expanded, you'll be able to use the `--select` and `--exclude` model selection syntax to filter the
models in the graph. For more information on model selection, check out the [dbt docs](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/model-selection-syntax).

Note that you can also right-click on models to interactively filter and explore the graph.

---

### More information

- [What is dbt](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/introduction)?
- Read the [dbt viewpoint](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/viewpoint)
- [Installation](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/installation)
- Join the [dbt Community](https://www.getdbt.com/community/) for questions and discussion
